{
  "doc_id": "20858",
  "text": "Previously, we noted that BCCIP is required for wildtype p53 activity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Loss of BCCIP expression in laryngeal cancers was associated with worse prognosis after radiation therapy but this was only true for tumors with wild-type p53 [CITATION_3] . Consistent with these reports, BCCIP negativity was found to be associated with breast cancers of wild-type p53 (Table 1 ). These observations imply that BCCIP's role in breast cancer may be independent of p53 status. However, p53 loss was able to rescue the brain development defect caused by BCCIP knockdown and to promote medulloblastoma [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , suggesting that p53 loss can contribute to BCCIP deficiency-induced tumor formation, at least in the context of medulloblastoma. Therefore, we asked whether there could be synergy between BCCIP deficiency and p53 loss for mammary tumorigenesis.",
